{"chunk_id": "9b080bcb-0fad-4e6f-a18a-bd2196aba9e3", "source_database": "ICMR", "document_title": "ICMR_NIN_Dietary_Guidelines_Real.pdf", "publication_version": "Latest", "chunk_sequence_number": 142, "content_type": "Medical Guideline", "language": "English", "text": "cancer, inflammatory joint diseases, asthma, diabetes etc. Raw and fresh vegetables like green leafy vegetables, carrots, fresh fruits including citrus and tomatoes have been identified as good sources of antioxidants (free radical- scavengers). The nutrients vitamin C and carotenoids that are present in these vegetables are also potential antioxidants. Different colored vegetable provide different antioxidants like orange colored provide beta-carotene, red provide lycopene, deep red provide betalines, blue and purple provide anthocynins. The Expert Committee of the Indian Council of Medical Research, taking into consideration the nutrient requirements, has recommended that every individual should consume at least 300 g of vegetables (GLV : 50 g; Other vegetables : 200 g; Roots & Tubers :", "embedding": [-0.021592479199171066, -0.013705468736588955, -0.07978202402591705, 0.06979227066040039, 0.032620079815387726, 0.026836857199668884, 0.007542873732745647, 0.06950719654560089, -0.0019183120457455516, -0.03902393952012062, 0.007475169841200113, -0.00017363214283250272, 0.01732708141207695, -0.11251651495695114, -0.027746042236685753, 0.06303619593381882, 0.056560564786195755, 0.022904418408870697, -0.10292905569076538, -0.02308017760515213, -0.04418041557073593, -0.008314351551234722, 0.054249681532382965, -0.03152850642800331, -0.05471612885594368, -0.10907606780529022, -0.0009021343430504203, -0.09182392805814743, -0.027397925034165382, 0.013736550696194172, 0.0519244521856308, 0.004400945268571377, 0.025576623156666756, -0.011305280029773712, -0.062221068888902664, -6.518440204672515e-05, -0.04711172729730606, -0.08355530351400375, -0.08464334160089493, -0.021125338971614838, -0.014113454148173332, 